               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430821-name-1559" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1559" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1559" type="surname" value="BAILEY"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1559" type="given" value="ELIZABETH"></interp>ELIZABETH BAILEY</persName>
                  </hi>. On the 10th of July the prisoners came to my house about ten o'clock—Bashford was a stranger—they sat in the kitchen a bit—a, man named Howe came to mend a mantel-piece—Lumsden said, "Mrs. Bailey, send the old man out for some beer"—I said, "There is no cause to spend your money"—he would persist in it, and put sixpence, a penny, and two halfpence in my hand—I sent Howe for the beer, and went up and let him in—I showed them all over the house, and while Lumsden kept me talking in the kitchen, Bashford <hi rend="italic">bolted</hi> with my husband's watch, which I had seen safe at twelve o'clock over the fire-place—I did not miss it till I sat down to dinner—this is it—it is No. 6394.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Lumsden.</hi> I had a friend with me, but it was not Bashford. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> I am convinced it was Bashford.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430821-name-1560" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1560" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1560" type="surname" value="BILSON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1560" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY BILSON</persName>
                  </hi>. I am assistant to Mr. Barker, a pawnbroker, in Hounds-ditch—this watch was pledged by Bashford on the 10th of July—I think about two or three o'clock—I live five miles from the prosecutrix.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430821-name-1561" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1561" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1561" type="surname" value="ANGUS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1561" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>WILLIAM ANGUS</persName>
                  </hi>. I am a stonemason, and live in Essex-street, Com<lb></lb>mercial-road. I know the prisoners—on the 7th of July I saw them in the Mile-end-road—I played at skittles with them at the Maid and Magpie in Stepney, but I never saw them speak to each other—I believe they came in company—I owed Lumsden 1<hi rend="italic">s</hi>.—he came to me in the Star and Garter for it, and asked if I was going to the Prince of Wales, and there I saw Bashford.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18430821-name-1562" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1562" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1562" type="surname" value="FRANCES"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18430821-name-1562" type="given" value="HENRY"></interp>HENRY FRANCES</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable N</hi> 227.) I went after Lumsden—I told him I took him on suspicion of stealing Mrs. Bailey's watch—on the way to the Court, next day, he asked if she missed anything—I said, "No"—I took</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="184308210205"></xptr>
               <p>Bashford next day—he said he came from Lee, in Kent—I found this dupli<lb></lb>cate on him—I heard both say they never saw each other before.</p>
               <p>(Lumsden received a good character.)</p>
